1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:11,660 --> 00:00:12,340
Where are you going?

3
00:00:12,340 --> 00:00:15,050
I said something, didn't I?

4
00:00:15,950 --> 00:00:17,950
But Dad, everyone's going.

5
00:00:18,150 --> 00:00:20,640
These kinds of protests are dangerous.

6
00:00:20,850 --> 00:00:23,900
But this is a peaceful protest against fascism.

7
00:00:24,350 --> 00:00:25,260
How peaceful?

8
00:00:25,750 --> 00:00:28,550
Well, we'll just peacefully express our opinion, calmly.

9
00:00:29,650 --> 00:00:33,050
Well, you can express it calmly right here in your room, can't you?

10
00:00:33,550 --> 00:00:34,750
I'll have an escort.

11
00:00:35,150 --> 00:00:36,950
You don't have to worry about me at all.

12
00:00:37,480 --> 00:00:37,960
Anarchy!

13
00:00:38,700 --> 00:00:39,180
Anarchy!

14
00:00:39,320 --> 00:00:40,420
Who's covering for the Nazis?

15
00:00:40,500 --> 00:00:41,440
It's the police!

16
00:00:41,760 --> 00:00:42,800
Nicely, Mr. Pacovsky.

17
00:00:44,630 --> 00:00:45,250
Hi, Lexa.

18
00:00:48,050 --> 00:00:49,350
What's in that backpack?

19
00:00:51,470 --> 00:00:52,410
Dice.

20
00:00:53,030 --> 00:00:54,110
He beat me again, Iva.

21
00:00:57,150 --> 00:00:58,150
So peacefully?

22
00:00:59,250 --> 00:01:00,550
Right here in your room, kiddo.

23
00:01:03,420 --> 00:01:03,900
Moron.

24
00:01:36,350 --> 00:01:38,050
Ozzak, what about that door?

25
00:01:38,600 --> 00:01:41,240
We clearly agreed you'd fix it this morning.

26
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:42,060
Is it necessary?

27
00:01:42,220 --> 00:01:44,020
It is necessary, it keeps getting stuck, see.

28
00:01:44,200 --> 00:01:46,720
Last time I almost spent the whole night here with Marcelka.

29
00:01:47,350 --> 00:01:49,580
Oh damn, this is where the fun ends.

30
00:01:49,580 --> 00:01:50,160
I'm on it.

31
00:01:51,950 --> 00:01:54,650
Watch, click it twice.

32
00:01:54,750 --> 00:01:56,050
Three strokes.

33
00:01:58,080 --> 00:01:58,980
And then...

34
00:01:58,980 --> 00:02:02,450
And done.

35
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:25,860
Can I help you?

36
00:02:26,100 --> 00:02:27,120
Hello, I'm looking for...

37
00:02:28,750 --> 00:02:30,350
Oh, you have Tokyo Dracula.

38
00:02:30,420 --> 00:02:31,640
Good eye, young man.

39
00:02:31,760 --> 00:02:32,580
And good taste.

40
00:02:32,820 --> 00:02:33,820
That's a solid piece of merch.

41
00:02:34,350 --> 00:02:35,850
But I've got a guy who imports it from Japan.

42
00:02:35,860 --> 00:02:37,480
That must cost a fortune.

43
00:02:37,720 --> 00:02:39,620
See, bro, you said nobody would appreciate it.

44
00:02:39,720 --> 00:02:42,160
No, I said nobody would buy it, that's different.

45
00:02:42,560 --> 00:02:43,640
Shall I ring it up?

46
00:02:43,780 --> 00:02:47,200
You must be doing pretty well if you can afford to order such rarities, huh?

47
00:02:47,460 --> 00:02:49,360
Well, can't complain.

48
00:02:49,480 --> 00:02:50,000
You can't.

49
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:51,950
That's a different situation now.

50
00:02:52,250 --> 00:02:52,950
Wait, wait.

51
00:02:57,750 --> 00:03:00,550
Think I scared him off with the ringing up?

52
00:03:04,150 --> 00:03:04,850
This is a holdup.

53
00:03:06,500 --> 00:03:06,820
Wait.

54
00:03:10,350 --> 00:03:11,250
This is a holdup.

55
00:03:14,340 --> 00:03:14,660
Wait.

56
00:03:18,950 --> 00:03:19,650
This is a holdup.

57
00:03:21,550 --> 00:03:24,110
Look, don't take it personally, kid, but I'm going for lunch.

58
00:03:24,110 --> 00:03:25,770
No wait, you can't.

59
00:03:26,550 --> 00:03:29,550
I can't? I have to, I'm hungry.

60
00:03:29,950 --> 00:03:31,410
Back it up.

61
00:03:31,950 --> 00:03:33,650
And hands up, Ozzak.

62
00:03:36,350 --> 00:03:37,960
I can't send you anywhere alone.

63
00:03:38,450 --> 00:03:42,150
When you rob a store, you can't let people leave.

64
00:03:42,750 --> 00:03:44,800
Nobody stays here long anyway.

65
00:03:45,150 --> 00:03:46,650
And you shut up too.

66
00:03:56,350 --> 00:03:59,750
Understand that these things are important, if everyone just sat at home, then...

67
00:04:00,350 --> 00:04:02,480
Yeah, but your dad forbade it.

68
00:04:02,650 --> 00:04:05,020
He can't forbid me from expressing my opinion.

69
00:04:05,350 --> 00:04:07,840
No, but he can forbid you from going outside.

70
00:04:08,250 --> 00:04:10,350
But I can hardly express my opinion at home.

71
00:04:10,800 --> 00:04:11,660
That's true.

72
00:04:11,660 --> 00:04:14,050
And when I do express it, nothing comes of it anyway.

73
00:04:14,080 --> 00:04:14,520
Right.

74
00:04:15,780 --> 00:04:17,480
I'm interested in your opinion, for example.

75
00:04:18,250 --> 00:04:19,340
I just mean, you're grounded.

76
00:04:19,340 --> 00:04:20,900
And that has to stop too.

77
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,000
Every time he doesn't know what to say, he grounds me.

78
00:04:23,080 --> 00:04:24,060
I'm going to have it out with him.

79
00:04:31,350 --> 00:04:32,950
Lexa, is it me or do you suddenly look better?

80
00:04:34,350 --> 00:04:37,150
Well, if you noticed, it's the balaclava.

81
00:04:39,650 --> 00:04:40,450
I got it for you.

82
00:05:10,890 --> 00:05:11,790
Not bad.

83
00:05:12,750 --> 00:05:13,750
Better than I thought.

84
00:05:13,950 --> 00:05:15,310
What kind of business did you pick?

85
00:05:15,550 --> 00:05:18,850
There's 50 crowns in the register and an Arakain badge.

86
00:05:19,550 --> 00:05:20,450
I forgot it there.

87
00:05:23,750 --> 00:05:25,940
So, bro, what's the plan?

88
00:05:26,150 --> 00:05:26,940
I have a plan?

89
00:05:26,940 --> 00:05:29,520
In these situations someone always has a plan.

90
00:05:29,790 --> 00:05:31,210
I don't have one, so you must.

91
00:05:32,350 --> 00:05:33,250
I have a plan.

92
00:05:33,850 --> 00:05:34,950
I'll wait till they leave.

93
00:05:36,150 --> 00:05:37,750
But they're taking all our CDs meanwhile.

94
00:05:38,350 --> 00:05:41,270
If it was some pop idiot, I wouldn't care, but this one's got taste.

95
00:05:41,270 --> 00:05:43,170
He's going to pick out my best stuff.

96
00:05:43,930 --> 00:05:45,270
Sorry, miss, we're closed.

97
00:05:46,250 --> 00:05:47,650
Are you from social services?

98
00:05:48,350 --> 00:05:49,750
We're closed.

99
00:05:50,460 --> 00:05:51,360
Run, boy!

100
00:05:51,960 --> 00:05:53,080
Run away!

101
00:05:53,220 --> 00:05:55,640
And take the salami and that Led Zeppelin collection too!

102
00:05:55,820 --> 00:05:58,620
It's hidden behind the Czech pop from the eighties!

103
00:06:01,150 --> 00:06:03,250
But you said someone stole those Zeppelins.

104
00:06:03,550 --> 00:06:05,350
They cost me two thousand without markup.

105
00:06:06,050 --> 00:06:06,950
I hid them.

106
00:06:07,790 --> 00:06:09,270
I was afraid someone would buy them.

107
00:06:13,650 --> 00:06:14,240
Sit down.

108
00:06:19,750 --> 00:06:20,900
Now this is really too much.

109
00:06:21,250 --> 00:06:23,360
You're going to tie me up every time I want to go out?

110
00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:24,840
No, just when we get robbed.

111
00:06:24,940 --> 00:06:25,860
Yeah, we got robbed.

112
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:26,980
What do they want to steal?

113
00:06:27,040 --> 00:06:27,820
Nirvana CDs?

114
00:06:28,340 --> 00:06:29,560
Christ, don't give them ideas.

115
00:06:30,420 --> 00:06:31,640
We have to hang in there.

116
00:06:31,820 --> 00:06:32,960
Maybe they'll leave soon.

117
00:06:33,180 --> 00:06:34,820
Then I might still make the protest.

118
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:36,660
Absolutely not, don't even think about it.

119
00:06:37,070 --> 00:06:38,150
Only over my dead body.

120
00:06:38,210 --> 00:06:40,110
You hired them so I can't go anywhere.

121
00:06:40,310 --> 00:06:41,330
Am I crazy?

122
00:06:42,650 --> 00:06:43,850
Got a plan yet?

123
00:06:44,350 --> 00:06:47,640
Well, Marcelka comes back from the dentist at eleven, maybe she'll sort it out.

124
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:48,200
How?

125
00:06:48,650 --> 00:06:51,660
I don't know, but Marcelka has a tendency to sort things out.

126
00:06:51,660 --> 00:06:52,100
Great.

127
00:06:53,920 --> 00:06:54,480
Wait.

128
00:06:55,950 --> 00:06:58,150
I'm actually looking forward to Marcelka coming.

129
00:06:58,400 --> 00:06:58,960
Tomas?

130
00:06:59,750 --> 00:07:02,500
We're not going to rob this stupid store.

131
00:07:02,500 --> 00:07:04,160
Can't you lock a door?

132
00:07:04,500 --> 00:07:05,060
Marcelka!

133
00:07:05,540 --> 00:07:06,680
Run away!

134
00:07:07,010 --> 00:07:08,270
Call the police!

135
00:07:08,630 --> 00:07:09,210
Let me go!

136
00:07:09,550 --> 00:07:10,030
Come here!

137
00:07:10,030 --> 00:07:11,250
Grab that creature!

138
00:07:16,870 --> 00:07:17,430
Sit down!

139
00:07:19,950 --> 00:07:23,850
We're screwed.

140
00:07:24,250 --> 00:07:26,150
Lexa will probably come looking for me.

141
00:07:28,910 --> 00:07:29,890
Definitely screwed.

142
00:07:36,510 --> 00:07:37,910
What are you taking off?

143
00:07:37,990 --> 00:07:38,730
We're leaving soon anyway.

144
00:07:39,110 --> 00:07:40,250
It's really itchy.

145
00:07:40,770 --> 00:07:42,230
You have to get used to it.

146
00:07:42,330 --> 00:07:43,090
There'll be cops there.

147
00:07:45,650 --> 00:07:47,050
Iva's been in there quite a while.

148
00:07:48,550 --> 00:07:50,250
Maybe that Mr. Pacovsky locked her in.

149
00:07:51,310 --> 00:07:52,370
He's a real tyrant.

150
00:07:54,050 --> 00:07:54,950
I'll go check it out.

151
00:07:55,350 --> 00:07:56,550
I'll be right back.

152
00:07:56,740 --> 00:07:58,020
Meanwhile, keep rolling the dice.

153
00:07:58,220 --> 00:07:59,180
Practice up.

154
00:08:22,100 --> 00:08:22,540
Occupied!

155
00:08:23,120 --> 00:08:24,040
We're already here!

156
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:25,440
Sure.

157
00:08:26,060 --> 00:08:26,800
See you then.

158
00:08:27,520 --> 00:08:27,960
Anarchy!

159
00:08:28,600 --> 00:08:29,040
Anarchy!

160
00:08:41,650 --> 00:08:43,450
We expected more from you.

161
00:08:44,950 --> 00:08:45,650
No, I'm really scared.

162
00:08:46,070 --> 00:08:47,270
Why are they taking so long?

163
00:08:47,310 --> 00:08:48,630
They grab the cash from the register and go, right?

164
00:08:48,790 --> 00:08:49,670
They're probably looking for a safe.

165
00:08:50,950 --> 00:08:52,350
Well, that'll take a while.

166
00:08:53,950 --> 00:08:55,550
We don't even have a safe.

167
00:08:56,420 --> 00:08:57,060
Or do we?

168
00:08:58,820 --> 00:09:01,880
See, you keep blaming me for not selling anything, and look how handy that is now.

169
00:09:02,240 --> 00:09:06,340
Thanks for reminding me of our pitiful financial situation at this moment.

170
00:09:06,620 --> 00:09:09,860
Dad, please, could you focus on what's actually important for a minute?

171
00:09:10,680 --> 00:09:11,820
My reserve beer.

172
00:09:11,820 --> 00:09:14,650
Well, that would be a tragedy.

173
00:09:19,150 --> 00:09:20,650
Jesus, you take it out too.

174
00:09:20,950 --> 00:09:23,650
No, I'm enjoying the quiet.

175
00:09:30,550 --> 00:09:33,750
Whoa, there are some protesters in the store.

176
00:09:36,450 --> 00:09:37,950
Think they're Iva's friends?

177
00:09:38,150 --> 00:09:39,740
I don't know, you should ask her.

178
00:09:40,150 --> 00:09:40,940
She wasn't there.

179
00:09:41,350 --> 00:09:42,160
And Mr. Pacovsky?

180
00:09:42,160 --> 00:09:42,620
Not either.

181
00:09:42,720 --> 00:09:43,620
And Mr. Ozzak?

182
00:09:43,840 --> 00:09:43,940
No.

183
00:09:44,060 --> 00:09:45,080
And Mrs. Marcelka?

184
00:09:45,240 --> 00:09:46,220
Just the two protesters.

185
00:09:46,890 --> 00:09:48,370
Doesn't that seem weird to you?

186
00:09:48,550 --> 00:09:48,750
No.

187
00:09:50,250 --> 00:09:56,550
Although maybe Mr. Pacovsky is also a fascist, that would explain why he wouldn't let Iva go.

188
00:09:57,050 --> 00:10:01,350
Lexa, or maybe those aren't protesters but robbers.

189
00:10:01,950 --> 00:10:02,850
Damn.

190
00:10:03,150 --> 00:10:04,250
I'm calling the police.

191
00:10:05,150 --> 00:10:06,050
Good idea.

192
00:10:06,650 --> 00:10:08,350
At least there'll be fewer at the protest.

193
00:10:10,970 --> 00:10:12,550
Hello, this is Sasa.

194
00:10:12,570 --> 00:10:14,030
I'd like to report a crime.

195
00:10:14,130 --> 00:10:19,290
At the store Two Chords, Horakova 11, there's no Mr. Pacovsky, no Mr. Ozzak, and no Mrs. Marcelka.

196
00:10:19,330 --> 00:10:20,790
And there are two robbers in there.

197
00:10:21,270 --> 00:10:22,830
What, I'm not joking?

198
00:10:23,070 --> 00:10:24,390
You're an amateur.

199
00:10:24,490 --> 00:10:25,990
Bomb, tell them there's a bomb.

200
00:10:26,150 --> 00:10:27,850
Careful, there's a bomb.

201
00:10:27,970 --> 00:10:28,910
Wonderful.

202
00:10:30,450 --> 00:10:31,810
Lex, how'd you come up with that?

203
00:10:31,950 --> 00:10:32,890
Totally by accident.

204
00:10:33,250 --> 00:10:35,050
It was just like before a math test.

205
00:10:43,750 --> 00:10:44,850
I'm going crazy.

206
00:10:45,050 --> 00:10:49,290
First you can't close the door properly and now you can't open it.

207
00:10:49,290 --> 00:10:52,170
You know, it was always fix that door, fix that door.

208
00:10:52,250 --> 00:10:53,870
And now it's handy that it won't open?

209
00:10:54,210 --> 00:10:57,050
I'd prefer it if they finally got out.

210
00:11:01,450 --> 00:11:03,550
Maybe I want to say something important.

211
00:11:11,550 --> 00:11:13,460
Nail file, back pocket.

212
00:11:13,460 --> 00:11:14,480
And she said important.

213
00:11:14,700 --> 00:11:17,900
Our lives are at stake, well the Zeppelins, and this one's thinking about nails.

214
00:11:18,380 --> 00:11:21,620
Uncle, Marcelka probably meant we could cut through the ropes.

215
00:11:22,650 --> 00:11:24,420
Ivuska, you're a genius.

216
00:11:24,420 --> 00:11:25,260
And what about me?

217
00:11:25,910 --> 00:11:27,210
You get the nail file out.

218
00:11:27,210 --> 00:11:29,110
Hard to do with my hands tied.

219
00:11:29,350 --> 00:11:30,670
You'll have to reach in for me.

220
00:11:30,670 --> 00:11:31,090
Where?

221
00:11:31,810 --> 00:11:34,630
In the back pocket for the nail file.

222
00:11:34,750 --> 00:11:36,370
I'm supposed to touch your butt?

223
00:11:36,570 --> 00:11:38,010
You have something against my butt?

224
00:11:38,270 --> 00:11:39,590
No, but I don't have anything for it either.

225
00:11:40,050 --> 00:11:40,510
You brute!

226
00:11:40,770 --> 00:11:43,190
Ozzak, behave yourself and touch Marcelka's butt.

227
00:11:43,570 --> 00:11:44,670
Forget it.

228
00:11:44,810 --> 00:11:46,290
He's not touching my butt.

229
00:11:46,350 --> 00:11:47,390
I'll find someone else.

230
00:11:49,850 --> 00:11:50,520
Stop that.

231
00:11:50,520 --> 00:11:50,980
Fine.

232
00:11:51,460 --> 00:11:53,220
It's something else, it's something else.

233
00:11:53,260 --> 00:11:54,700
It's a cold twelve-pack.

234
00:11:54,720 --> 00:11:55,480
It's a cold...

235
00:11:56,390 --> 00:11:57,290
I got it.

236
00:11:59,550 --> 00:12:00,450
Are you satisfied?

237
00:12:00,550 --> 00:12:01,450
No, we're not satisfied.

238
00:12:02,990 --> 00:12:04,150
Well then, what else would you like?

239
00:12:05,050 --> 00:12:08,650
For you to take the nail file out of my pocket.

240
00:12:10,850 --> 00:12:11,650
Oh right.

241
00:12:13,420 --> 00:12:13,940
Again.

242
00:12:19,540 --> 00:12:20,400
Here you go.

243
00:12:27,050 --> 00:12:28,950
You, you're coming with me.

244
00:12:38,250 --> 00:12:40,550
I told you to grab something valuable if they don't have money.

245
00:12:41,820 --> 00:12:45,200
It's hard for an independent music store to make money.

246
00:12:45,870 --> 00:12:47,110
Are you crazy, woman?

247
00:12:47,270 --> 00:12:48,850
This is the best thing we've got here.

248
00:12:49,330 --> 00:12:49,810
Fine.

249
00:12:50,630 --> 00:12:51,750
Then wrap it up.

250
00:12:51,950 --> 00:12:53,270
No, not this one.

251
00:12:53,390 --> 00:12:54,590
Otherwise take anything you want.

252
00:12:54,870 --> 00:12:56,710
Even my reserve beer behind the counter.

253
00:13:01,540 --> 00:13:02,020
Yeah.

254
00:13:02,020 --> 00:13:04,820
Okay, you've got the beer, now give me the record back.

255
00:13:05,150 --> 00:13:06,750
I make the rules here.

256
00:13:07,350 --> 00:13:10,850
And you're going to tell me why the door won't open.

257
00:13:10,950 --> 00:13:16,500
Oh, the door won't open, it won't open for anyone who doesn't know the special trick.

258
00:13:16,850 --> 00:13:19,620
Then you better tell me that trick.

259
00:13:19,750 --> 00:13:22,450
Ha, you can torture me, I won't say a word.

260
00:13:22,550 --> 00:13:24,650
As you wish.

261
00:13:28,560 --> 00:13:29,980
There's too much fat on that.

262
00:13:31,350 --> 00:13:32,750
Hand me the record.

263
00:13:36,560 --> 00:13:37,750
Please.

264
00:13:38,550 --> 00:13:41,730
Fair terrorists release women, children, and rock LPs first.

265
00:13:41,730 --> 00:13:43,090
We're not fair.

266
00:13:43,650 --> 00:13:44,930
Enough, stop it.

267
00:13:45,550 --> 00:13:47,150
Will you tell me your trick?

268
00:13:47,190 --> 00:13:47,870
I didn't say that.

269
00:13:47,870 --> 00:13:48,950
I wanted you to stop.

270
00:13:48,950 --> 00:13:51,390
Fine, I'm counting to three.

271
00:13:51,950 --> 00:13:54,050
And then this kid tells me your best record.

272
00:13:56,110 --> 00:13:57,410
You're not even human.

273
00:13:57,410 --> 00:14:01,130
Ozzak, open that door right now.

274
00:14:01,350 --> 00:14:03,050
We're not going to negotiate with them.

275
00:14:03,650 --> 00:14:06,750
Next month you get all shifts with Marcelka.

276
00:14:07,950 --> 00:14:08,870
I'll tell you everything.

277
00:14:08,870 --> 00:14:09,950
Dude, untie me.

278
00:14:24,050 --> 00:14:24,550
Smoke on the Water.

279
00:14:37,650 --> 00:14:38,130
Oh damn.

280
00:14:38,750 --> 00:14:39,750
What's happening?

281
00:14:40,050 --> 00:14:43,150
Last time it popped like that, the fire department had to come.

282
00:14:43,350 --> 00:14:45,950
Please, get him out of here, I'm scared.

283
00:14:47,750 --> 00:14:51,350
I'll find a wrench and we'll get out.

284
00:14:51,830 --> 00:14:52,310
Wait.

285
00:14:53,750 --> 00:14:56,350
But I always have all shifts with Marcelka.

286
00:15:12,650 --> 00:15:14,050
Hey, I wanted to ask you something.

287
00:15:14,550 --> 00:15:15,950
If you'd go out tonight?

288
00:15:15,950 --> 00:15:17,310
What?

289
00:15:18,150 --> 00:15:20,510
Like, after your mom finishes robbing my dad's store?

290
00:15:20,650 --> 00:15:24,150
Well, professional and private life shouldn't mix.

291
00:15:26,350 --> 00:15:28,250
I heard you're going to the protest.

292
00:15:28,430 --> 00:15:30,350
I wanted to too, but my mom wouldn't let me.

293
00:15:30,570 --> 00:15:32,150
Your mother is a sensible woman.

294
00:15:32,650 --> 00:15:34,850
As long as she's not robbing stores.

295
00:15:35,450 --> 00:15:36,950
What are you doing Thursday evening?

296
00:15:36,970 --> 00:15:37,890
Would you go...

297
00:15:37,890 --> 00:15:39,150
Absolutely not.

298
00:15:39,250 --> 00:15:41,470
The only place you two are going together is court.

299
00:15:41,550 --> 00:15:43,330
You as the defendant and her as the witness.

300
00:15:43,510 --> 00:15:45,150
Wait, we have a lot in common.

301
00:15:45,750 --> 00:15:48,290
Like, we both have parents who restrict us.

302
00:15:48,290 --> 00:15:49,470
Yes, Mom isn't bad.

303
00:15:49,530 --> 00:15:51,970
She tells us that protests won't pay the bills.

304
00:15:52,030 --> 00:15:53,330
That nothing beats a good break-in.

305
00:15:54,850 --> 00:15:55,850
We've got that in common.

306
00:15:56,450 --> 00:15:58,700
Maybe we really should go out sometime and talk about it.

307
00:15:58,700 --> 00:15:59,400
Wait a second.

308
00:16:00,040 --> 00:16:01,440
Ivuska, now he tied you up.

309
00:16:01,560 --> 00:16:02,260
What do you mean wait?

310
00:16:02,480 --> 00:16:05,280
Tied up in a closet or grounded in an apartment, it's the same in the end, right?

311
00:16:05,400 --> 00:16:06,140
So should I go for it?

312
00:16:09,150 --> 00:16:10,850
This is how all my dates end.

313
00:16:13,110 --> 00:16:13,550
Good lord.

314
00:16:14,510 --> 00:16:16,390
Brats outside and you're in here flirting.

315
00:16:16,750 --> 00:16:18,130
Mom, we're here...

316
00:16:18,130 --> 00:16:19,650
This girl is not for you.

317
00:16:19,930 --> 00:16:20,630
Told you.

318
00:16:20,890 --> 00:16:21,550
A sensible woman.

319
00:16:21,650 --> 00:16:23,170
You deserve someone better.

320
00:16:23,670 --> 00:16:24,550
How better?

321
00:16:24,550 --> 00:16:25,130
What do you mean better?

322
00:16:25,250 --> 00:16:27,910
When your moron can't even rob their store.

323
00:16:28,290 --> 00:16:30,070
Your store can't be robbed.

324
00:16:30,210 --> 00:16:32,290
That's against the laws of nature.

325
00:16:33,150 --> 00:16:33,790
Get up.

326
00:16:43,350 --> 00:16:44,150
That must be them.

327
00:16:54,200 --> 00:16:54,840
Excuse me.

328
00:16:57,360 --> 00:16:58,180
Good day.

329
00:16:58,750 --> 00:17:02,760
I'm a psychologist from the organized crime unit of the Czech Republic police.

330
00:17:02,760 --> 00:17:04,400
That's commendable work.

331
00:17:05,050 --> 00:17:06,720
The police commit loads of crimes.

332
00:17:07,350 --> 00:17:08,150
Well, no.

333
00:17:08,950 --> 00:17:10,850
The police investigate crimes.

334
00:17:11,220 --> 00:17:12,660
It's a vicious circle.

335
00:17:14,050 --> 00:17:15,480
The bomb thing, that was me.

336
00:17:15,480 --> 00:17:16,280
Lock me up.

337
00:17:16,380 --> 00:17:22,000
No, I'm not an investigator, I'm a psychologist, a specialist in delivering bad news to relatives of crime victims.

338
00:17:22,600 --> 00:17:28,200
I'm here to gently tell Miss Iva Pacovska that her father and uncle are in mortal danger.

339
00:17:29,150 --> 00:17:29,950
What?

340
00:17:30,450 --> 00:17:31,650
My God, it's you.

341
00:17:32,950 --> 00:17:36,350
I mumbled it, sorry, this is my first assignment and I'm terribly sorry.

342
00:17:38,850 --> 00:17:39,670
You hug?

343
00:17:39,950 --> 00:17:40,450
Yes, I'm trained for it.

344
00:17:40,650 --> 00:17:44,950
We have to provide all assistance to relatives of victims.

345
00:17:47,550 --> 00:17:48,850
All assistance?

346
00:17:49,450 --> 00:17:50,950
This is just a neighbor.

347
00:17:51,250 --> 00:17:52,950
I'm the one who needs help here.

348
00:17:54,850 --> 00:17:56,150
Are you Iva Pacovska?

349
00:17:56,550 --> 00:17:57,350
I'm the son.

350
00:17:57,850 --> 00:17:58,410
Ivan.

351
00:17:59,650 --> 00:18:01,050
You must have an error there.

352
00:18:02,050 --> 00:18:03,850
This would happen to me.

353
00:18:03,850 --> 00:18:04,950
But you're not...

354
00:18:04,950 --> 00:18:07,150
Go away, you random neighbor!

355
00:18:11,650 --> 00:18:12,250
Daddy, Uncle.

356
00:18:14,150 --> 00:18:15,050
I think I could use a little hug.

357
00:18:16,990 --> 00:18:18,490
What got into you?

358
00:18:18,910 --> 00:18:21,730
Miss, it would really be better if you left, because Ivan here.

359
00:18:22,180 --> 00:18:23,380
Needs professional care.

360
00:18:25,250 --> 00:18:27,850
Fine, I'll wait outside the door.

361
00:18:28,850 --> 00:18:30,150
Don't let anyone in!

362
00:18:31,050 --> 00:18:33,050
I couldn't bear the press attention.

363
00:18:34,850 --> 00:18:37,350
You know, sometimes the world seems so cruel to me.

364
00:18:38,650 --> 00:18:39,750
I'll support you.

365
00:18:41,850 --> 00:18:43,650
Then I'll lean on you, if you don't mind.

366
00:18:56,180 --> 00:18:57,240
Come on, pick up.

367
00:18:57,850 --> 00:18:58,850
Who is it?

368
00:18:58,900 --> 00:18:59,780
Who do you think?

369
00:18:59,880 --> 00:19:00,360
Police.

370
00:19:00,360 --> 00:19:02,120
You're going to negotiate now.

371
00:19:02,250 --> 00:19:04,350
They don't have you in the voice database.

372
00:19:05,340 --> 00:19:06,020
Hello?

373
00:19:06,340 --> 00:19:07,020
What?

374
00:19:09,550 --> 00:19:10,070
What?

375
00:19:11,260 --> 00:19:11,780
No!

376
00:19:13,050 --> 00:19:14,280
Are you crazy?

377
00:19:14,280 --> 00:19:16,300
I said you should negotiate.

378
00:19:16,480 --> 00:19:17,960
No, that was some kid from the neighbors.

379
00:19:18,040 --> 00:19:20,640
He asked if we could drag out the robbery as long as possible.

380
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:26,520
Hello?

381
00:19:27,650 --> 00:19:28,250
Yes?

382
00:19:28,850 --> 00:19:30,120
What, our demands?

383
00:19:30,350 --> 00:19:32,350
Well, I don't know, just free us.

384
00:19:32,450 --> 00:19:33,560
I'm sorry?

385
00:19:33,560 --> 00:19:34,780
Right, their demands.

386
00:19:34,780 --> 00:19:37,250
Do you have any demands?

387
00:19:37,680 --> 00:19:38,960
Hang on, they're looking for them.

388
00:19:40,140 --> 00:19:41,820
Yeah, got it, I'll read.

389
00:19:42,280 --> 00:19:42,800
So...

390
00:19:43,250 --> 00:19:45,580
A car with a full tank.

391
00:19:45,580 --> 00:19:46,160
With a turbo.

392
00:19:47,950 --> 00:19:57,140
A plane at Ruzyne airport, GPS navigation, a manual on how to fly a plane, and a month's supply of food.

393
00:19:57,350 --> 00:19:58,540
And peanut butter.

394
00:19:59,150 --> 00:20:01,150
And peanut butter.

395
00:20:02,750 --> 00:20:03,590
Yeah, I'll pass it on.

396
00:20:03,950 --> 00:20:06,630
Listen, they want one hostage for each item.

397
00:20:06,750 --> 00:20:13,650
So that's a car, GPS navigation, a month's supply of food, peanut butter.

398
00:20:13,850 --> 00:20:14,850
The plane.

399
00:20:15,210 --> 00:20:15,730
Five.

400
00:20:17,150 --> 00:20:18,050
Damn.

401
00:20:18,950 --> 00:20:20,050
We need one more.

402
00:20:20,990 --> 00:20:21,890
Know anyone?

403
00:20:22,010 --> 00:20:23,170
Maybe from the neighborhood?

404
00:20:25,150 --> 00:20:26,760
We have four, we'll give four.

405
00:20:26,760 --> 00:20:27,100
Fine.

406
00:20:27,100 --> 00:20:30,650
Listen, they say only four.

407
00:20:31,750 --> 00:20:32,620
Yeah, I'll pass it on.

408
00:20:32,950 --> 00:20:36,740
Listen, according to some EU directive they shouldn't even be talking to you, right?

409
00:20:36,740 --> 00:20:37,620
So five or nothing.

410
00:20:40,850 --> 00:20:42,760
Then drop the peanut butter.

411
00:20:43,750 --> 00:20:44,440
Yeah, that's reasonable.

412
00:20:44,440 --> 00:20:45,500
Well, Mom.

413
00:20:46,250 --> 00:20:48,870
Can't we drop the plane instead?

414
00:20:49,350 --> 00:20:50,550
That's non-negotiable.

415
00:20:51,270 --> 00:20:52,170
Go get them.

416
00:20:52,230 --> 00:20:52,630
Sure.

417
00:20:54,150 --> 00:20:57,450
Hey, so in the end, drop the peanut butter.

418
00:20:57,550 --> 00:20:58,550
Fine.

419
00:21:02,350 --> 00:21:03,550
All right, we're done here, mama.

420
00:21:03,880 --> 00:21:05,620
I'm done with this.

421
00:21:05,880 --> 00:21:07,500
Sorry, Mom, I got distracted.

422
00:21:10,650 --> 00:21:12,250
So nobody do anything stupid.

423
00:21:19,250 --> 00:21:20,550
Let my dad go.

424
00:21:20,750 --> 00:21:21,650
Or what?

425
00:21:22,250 --> 00:21:23,050
Or...

426
00:21:23,450 --> 00:21:26,260
Or we'll give your boy a buzz cut.

427
00:21:26,650 --> 00:21:27,400
Mom, don't be crazy.

428
00:21:27,850 --> 00:21:29,050
What if they actually pull the trigger?

429
00:21:30,250 --> 00:21:33,650
You think I put bullets in it?

430
00:21:48,550 --> 00:21:53,450
According to specialist literature, hug therapy works mostly on children under five.

431
00:21:54,150 --> 00:21:55,450
Is it really helping you?

432
00:21:55,450 --> 00:21:56,090
I'd like more.

433
00:21:58,350 --> 00:21:59,850
But ten minutes maximum.

434
00:22:00,550 --> 00:22:02,520
Otherwise the maternal fixation will be disrupted.

435
00:22:02,520 --> 00:22:03,400
No risk of that with me.

436
00:22:05,230 --> 00:22:05,790
Thanks.

437
00:22:07,150 --> 00:22:10,450
You're really helping me here, this is my first assignment, and a hostage situation on top of it.

438
00:22:10,950 --> 00:22:11,960
You're wonderful.

439
00:22:12,450 --> 00:22:14,350
I'll write a thank-you note to the commander.

440
00:22:14,970 --> 00:22:16,470
That would really help me.

441
00:22:19,150 --> 00:22:21,090
How about that hug therapy?

442
00:22:21,350 --> 00:22:22,810
Can we increase the dose a bit?

443
00:22:22,810 --> 00:22:23,490
Please.

444
00:22:28,750 --> 00:22:30,450
So you never trusted me.

445
00:22:30,750 --> 00:22:33,880
I did, but I wasn't completely sure.

446
00:22:33,880 --> 00:22:34,780
And what if things went wrong?

447
00:22:35,250 --> 00:22:37,220
Things always went wrong because of you.

448
00:22:37,220 --> 00:22:38,860
And I was there to protect you.

449
00:22:38,860 --> 00:22:42,150
But I'm old enough to protect myself, if you'd let me.

450
00:22:42,360 --> 00:22:43,600
I want to make you proud, Mom.

451
00:22:43,940 --> 00:22:44,340
Proud?

452
00:22:44,340 --> 00:22:49,520
You know what would make me proud? If you were a proper criminal.

453
00:22:49,650 --> 00:22:54,880
You know, projecting your own ambitions onto children is often a source of problems.

454
00:22:54,880 --> 00:22:57,000
Well yeah, actually the kid's not that bad.

455
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:01,420
I was actually scared of him for a moment, if only you didn't keep nagging him.

456
00:23:01,680 --> 00:23:02,520
Iva, how dare you talk like that?

457
00:23:03,150 --> 00:23:06,350
I understand you, you mean well, but the kid doesn't get it yet.

458
00:23:06,550 --> 00:23:09,090
She can't mean well when she keeps hassling him like this.

459
00:23:09,350 --> 00:23:10,990
The kid ends up totally crushed.

460
00:23:10,990 --> 00:23:12,830
So let him try something on his own.

461
00:23:12,970 --> 00:23:14,390
Well, it doesn't have to be anything big.

462
00:23:14,570 --> 00:23:17,090
Maybe just a newsstand, or some old lady.

463
00:23:17,390 --> 00:23:18,730
Have you lost your mind?

464
00:23:19,030 --> 00:23:20,070
Not completely alone.

465
00:23:20,170 --> 00:23:23,970
I think it'd be more than enough if you just followed him discreetly from a distance.

466
00:23:25,550 --> 00:23:27,550
I never wanted to do this job anyway.

467
00:23:29,050 --> 00:23:31,250
So you'd rather go to that math and physics school?

468
00:23:33,070 --> 00:23:33,370
Yeah.

469
00:23:53,150 --> 00:24:27,150
Skin-to-skin therapy is recommended for severe hypothermia.

470
00:24:51,750 --> 00:25:03,250
Dear Iva, in the end everything turned out fine.

471
00:25:03,750 --> 00:25:07,050
It turned out the judge also lived with his parents for a long time.

472
00:25:07,550 --> 00:25:12,350
Mom got five years, but she seems happy there because she only calls me once a month.

473
00:25:12,950 --> 00:25:16,850
Although maybe that's because she's only allowed one phone call a month.

474
00:25:19,450 --> 00:25:21,650
Well, nice letter.

475
00:25:22,250 --> 00:25:24,430
Except you could've just mailed it.

476
00:25:24,430 --> 00:25:25,670
I wanted to see you again.

477
00:25:27,350 --> 00:25:29,550
Well, you're old enough, decide what you want.

478
00:25:30,450 --> 00:25:32,850
Dad, that's great, thanks.

479
00:25:34,450 --> 00:25:35,750
So no.

480
00:25:35,750 --> 00:25:38,950
I probably won't have time for about a year anyway.

481
00:25:40,050 --> 00:25:40,950
We have to go.

482
00:25:41,350 --> 00:25:44,350
We have maternal detachment therapy.

483
00:25:44,960 --> 00:25:45,480
Goodbye.

484
00:25:50,350 --> 00:25:51,450
I'm proud of you.

485
00:25:51,690 --> 00:25:52,210
Why?

486
00:25:52,210 --> 00:25:56,750
Well, how you peacefully expressed your views on a social issue at that protest.

487
00:25:56,950 --> 00:25:59,090
I'm glad you let me go in the end.

488
00:25:59,090 --> 00:25:59,910
You were right.

489
00:26:00,350 --> 00:26:01,350
It was peaceful.

490
00:26:02,350 --> 00:26:04,450
So you didn't even have to come with me in the end.

491
00:26:23,870 --> 00:26:24,390
Good?

492
00:26:26,060 --> 00:26:26,580
Excellent.

493
00:26:29,350 --> 00:26:30,250
Aren't you cold?

494
00:26:31,100 --> 00:26:31,620
Yeah.

495
00:26:32,220 --> 00:26:32,520
Yeah?

496
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:33,120
Yeah.

